[[Image:Gunston hall loc tree.jpg|thumb|300px|View of Gunston Hall from the northwest]]
'''Gunston Hall''' is an 18th-century [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] [[mansion]] near the [[Potomac River]] in [[Mason Neck, Virginia|Mason Neck]], [[Virginia]].<ref name="HAinFC">{{cite web
| url = http://www.fxva.com/fxva/historic_attract.html#gunston
| title = Historic Attractions in Farifax County, Virginia - Gunston Hall
| accessdate = 2006-08-31
| year = © 2006
| publisher = FXVA
}}</ref><ref name="GHPmain">{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/
| title = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
}} Also hosted on [http://look.net/gunstonhall/ look.net].</ref> The house was the home of the [[Founding Fathers of the United States|Founder]] [[George Mason]] and once was the centre of a 5500-acre [[plantation]].<ref name="GHPshop">
{{cite web
| url = http://look.net/gunstonhall/gift/catalogindex.tpl
| title =  Gunston Hall Museum Shop
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref> Construction of Gunston Hall began in about 1755<ref name="americanfurniture">{{cite book
 | last = Beckerdite
 | first = Luke et al
 | title = American Furniture 1994
 | origyear = 1994
 | url = http://www.chipstone.org/publications/1994AF/TableCont/1994Contents.html
 | accessdate = 2006-08-31
 | publisher = Chipstone
 | chapter = Architect-Designed Furniture in Eighteenth-Century Virginia: The Work of William Buckland and William Bernard Sears
 | chapterurl = http://www.chipstone.org/publications/1994AF/Index1994Beck.html
 | quote =
 }}</ref> and was completed in 1759<ref name="GHPtimeline">{{cite web
| url = http://look.net/gunstonhall/georgemason/timeline.html#overview
| title = George Mason Chronology
| accessdate = 2006-08-31
| year = ©1997
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref>.

Gunston Hall is believed to be designed by William Buckland, a carpenter/joiner and [[indentured servant]] from England. Buckland later went on to design a number of fine buildings in Virginia and Maryland. Both he and William Bernard Sears, another indentured servant, are believed to have created the fancy woodwork and interior carving. Gunston's interior design combines elements of [[rococo]], [[chinoiserie]], and [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic]] styles, an unusual contrast the tendency for simple decoration in Virginia at this time.<ref name="GHPfirstfloor">{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/tour/welcome.html
| title = Architecturally Speaking
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| work = House Tour
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref> Although chinoiserie was popular in [[Britain]], Gunston is thought to be the only house with this decoration at this time in America.<ref name="GHPparlour">
{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/tour/parlor.html
| title = Parlor
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| work = House Tour
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref> In 1792, [[Thomas Jefferson]] attended [[George Mason]] at his death bed at Gunston Hall.<ref name="pittman">{{cite web
| url = http://rcarterpittman.org/essays/Mason/George_Mason_of_Gunston_Hall.html
| title = George Mason of Gunston Hall (1725 - 1792)
| accessdate = 2006-08-31
| last = Pittman
| first = R. Carter
| coauthors = edited by LeFevre, Joel T
| year = 1953
| publisher = Rcarterpittman.org. Originally published in the Autograph Collector's Journal, Spring Convention Edition
}}</ref> After Mason's death later that year, the house continued to be used as a residence for many years.<ref name="GHParchaeo-pg2>{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/archaeology/archaeology2.html
| title = Gunston Hall's Archaeology Program
| accessdate = 2006-08-31
| work = House and Grounds
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
| pages = 2
}}</ref>  It is now a museum and is open to the public.<ref name="GHPmain" />

The [[USS Gunston Hall (LSD-44)|USS ''Gunston Hall'']] was named for the mansion.<ref name="ship-official">{{cite web
| url = http://www.gunston-hall.navy.mil/index_files/Page673.htm
| title = History
| accessdate = 2006-09-01
| work = USS Gunston Hall (LSD044) - Defending the Constitution
| publisher = U.S. Navy
}}
</ref><ref name="ship-unofficial">{{cite web
| url = http://www.navysite.de/ships/lsd44.htm#about
| title = About the Ship’s Name, about the Sage of Gunston Hall
| accessdate = 2006-08-24
| last = Doehring
| first = Thoralf (webmaster)
| work = USS Gunston Hall (LSD 44)
| publisher = Unofficial US Navy Site
}}</ref>

== First floor ==
[[Image:Gunston-Hall-main-passage.jpg|thumb|300px|Central passage]]
The first floor of the house is divided in two by a central passage, leading from a door in the front to a door in the back, with a staircase running up on the left side. On the left of the central passage is the primary chamber (or bedroom) in the front, and the little parlour in the back. Between the primary chamber and the little parlour is a smaller passage, leading to a service staircase and a small, side stairway. According to the Gunston Hall Plantation official website, on the right side of the house is a parlour in the front, and a dining room in the back.<ref name="GHPfirstfloor" /> According to the Historic American Buildings Survey (part of the US National Park Service), on the right side of the house the dining room is in the front and the palladian room is in the back.<ref name="HABSfirstfloor">
{{cite web
| url = http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/displayPhoto.pl?path=/pnp/habshaer/va/va0400/va0433/sheet&topImages=00005a.gif&topLinks=00005r.tif,00005a.tif&title=&displayProfile=0
| title = First floor plan
| accessdate = 2006-08-24
| work = Gunston Hall Drawings
| publisher = Historic American Buildings Survey (part of the US National Park Service)
}}</ref>

The central passage is lined by six symmetrical [[Doric order|Doric]]-style pilasters. A double arch, with a carved pine cone, divides the front of the passage from the back. In the front, there are 4 doors placed opposite each other, although one is a fake door for symmetry. The front of the hall is covered in wallpaper, while the back has raised painted panelling.<ref name="GHPpassage">
{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/tour/passage.html
| title = Central Passage
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| work = House Tour
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref>

The primary chamber was a private, non-public room, and was less ornate than the public rooms. Towards the end of Mason's life, it was painted in emerald green, which was considered a desirable colour. The windows had pocket shutters, and are also believed to be the only windows in the house to have curtains during Mason's lifetime.<ref name="GHPchamber">
{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/tour/chamber.html
| title = Chamber
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| work = House Tour
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref>

The little parlour was also non-public, and decorated plainly. The walls were painted a neutral grey. Above the fireplace was a split pediment overmantel (a rectangle, and a partial triangle above that). During Mason's lifetime, the rectangle would have contained either a painting or a mirror. On either side of the fireplace are deep-shelved beaufats (niches) to store and display the tableware, with doors to secure valuable possessions.<ref name="GHPlittleparlor">
{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/tour/littleparlor.html
| title = Little Parlor
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| work = House Tour
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref>

[[Image:Gunston-Hall-front.jpg|thumb|300px|Gunston Hall in May 2006, seen from the front]]
The parlor, according to the Gunston Hall Plantation official website (the dining room according to the Historic American Buildings Survey),<ref name="HABSfirstfloor" /> was a public, ornately decorated room. The walls are painted a yellow ochre, and the woodwork is Chinese-style. The wall of the fireplace has a mantel decorated with [[fretwork]], pagoda-like scalloped mouldings, as well as canopies topped by pine cone finials. Above the doors are similar canopies, which might have displayed Chinese porcelain vases or ceramic figures. The two long windows are topped by scalloped pediments, decorated with fretwork. During Mason's lifetime, 3 of the walls were probably wallpapered. During the 1700s, chinoese (Chinese-style) design was popular in Great Britain, however no other rooms with [[chinoiserie]] woodwork are known to have existed in colonial America.<ref name="GHPparlor" />

The dining room, according to the Gunston Hall Plantation official website (the palladian room according to the Historic American Buildings Survey),<ref name="HABSfirstfloor" /> was also public, and was the most elaborately decorated in the house. The classical woodwork shows touches of the fashionable [[Rococo#Architecture|rococo]] design. The fireplace wall has an ornate chimney breast. On either side of the fireplace are beaufats, these ones with shallower shelves than in the little parlour, and no doors. Classical broken pediments top the chimney breast and the beaufats. The floor is comprised carefully matched blind-dowelled planks, an expensive feature. Egg-and-dart carved patterns surround the black-walnut entry doors. During Mason's lifetime, painted or decorated paper covered the thin pine panelling on the walls. The two windows look out onto Mason's garden.<ref name="GHPdiningroom">
{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/tour/diningroom.html
| title = Dining Room
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| work = House Tour
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref>

== Second floor ==
[[Image:Gunston-Hall-back.jpg|thumb|300px|Gunston Hall in May 2006, seen from the back looking through the garden]]
Unlike other 18th century houses of Gunston Hall's stature, the layout of the second floor is unlike the layout of the floor below. A narrow passage runs sideways through the upper level, leading to seven bedchambers and a storage room. At the top of the main stairway is a tri-part arch with fluted pillars, separating the passageway from a small gallery overlooking the staircase. The smaller service staircase comes up opposite the storage room.<ref name="GHPsecondfloor">
{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/tour/secondfloor.html
| title = Second Floor
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| work = House Tour
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref>

Of the bedchambers, the four corner rooms were considered the nicest. Each of the four corner bedchambers had a fireplace. Their fireplaces and surrounds did have some architectural detail. The corner rooms had two or three instead of one, which is all the inner bedchambers had. The walls of the corner bedchambers were painted with more expensive shades, such as Prussian blue or verdigris. The attic could be accessed through one of the inner bedrooms.<ref name="GHPsecondfloor" />

The storage closet, or lumber room, had no exterior window, but instead received light from a window to the stairwell, as there was an exterior window above the staircase landing.<ref name="GHPsecondfloor" />

== Basement ==
Gunston Hall also has a basement, which has a main passage and four rooms like the floor above it. Three staircases lead down to the basement. The basement contains four brick arched chimney supports, and nine small windows.<ref name=HABSbasement>
{{cite web
| url = http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/displayPhoto.pl?path=/pnp/habshaer/va/va0400/va0433/sheet&topImages=00004a.gif&topLinks=00004r.tif,00004a.tif&title=&displayProfile=0
| title = Basement plan - Reflected ceiling plan
| accessdate = 2006-08-24
| work = Gunston Hall Drawings
| publisher = Historic American Buildings Survey (part of the US National Park Service)
}}
</ref><ref name="HABSchimneysupport">
{{cite web
| url = http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/displayPhoto.pl?path=/pnp/habshaer/va/va0400/va0433/photos&topImages=161624pr.jpg&topLinks=161624pv.jpg,161624pu.tif&title=71.%20%20DETAIL%20OF%20CHIMNEY%20SUPPORT,%20EAST%20WALL%20OF%20BASEMENT%20%3cbr%3eHABS%20VA,30-LORT,1-71&displayProfile=0
| title = 71. Detail of chimney support, east wall of basement HABS VA,30-LORT,1-71
| accessdate = 2006-08-24
| work = Gunston Hall Black & White Photos
| publisher = Historic American Buildings Survey (part of the US National Park Service)
}}</ref> In 1975, a cast iron stove was excavated from the basement. The style of the stove suggests it is from the 18th or early 19th century.<ref name="HABSheating">{{cite web
| url = http://www.gunstonhall.org/architecture/roomuse/heating.html
| title = Recommended Objects: Heating
| accessdate = 2006-08-24
| year = 2002
| work = Gunston Hall Room Use Study
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref> Around 1986, a "shallow subsurface perimeter drainage system" was built about 4 feet away from the foundation walls, due to an excess ground moisture. This significantly reduced standing water in the basement.<ref>{{cite journal
 | quotes = 
 | last = Park
 | first = Sharon C.
 | year = 1996
 | title = Diagnosing Moisture in Historic Buildings
 | journal = Cultural Resource Management: Technology
 | volume = 19
 | issue = 7
 | pages = 1, 4
 | doi = 
