 | url = http://crm.cr.nps.gov/archive/19-7/19-7-2.pdf
 | format = [[PDF]]
 | accessdate = 2006-10-29
 }} Also see [http://72.14.209.104/search?q=cache:7zTn9YAhfZ0J:crm.cr.nps.gov/archive/19-7/19-7-2.pdf+%22Gunston+Hall%22+basement&hl=en&gl=us&ct=clnk&cd=12&client=firefox Google's HTML cache].</ref>

== Garden ==
[[Image:Gunston South View LOC.jpg|thumb|300px|View of garden from Gunston Hall looking southwards from a second floor window]]
The garden was located behind the house, or on the southern side. The garden was grown above a man-made level platform where there used to be a hill, and was exactly one acre in area. A gravel path runs from the back of the house to the southern edge, and was 12 feet wide during Mason's time period, the same width as the central passage in the house and the portico. Today, the path is narrower, crowded by boxwoods that are now about 250 years old. The path ends in an overlook extending out from the steep edge of the garden. From here, the Potomac river can be seen. The view would have probably been more impressive during Mason's time, when the trees were cleared. The garden was most likely broken into four rectangles, with additional gravel paths running through and around it. The rectangles closer to the house were probably shorter than the rectangles further away, in order to give the illusion from the house of all rectangles being the same size.<ref name="GHPgarden">
{{cite web
| url = http://gunstonhall.org/archaeology/discovergarden.html
| title = Discovering George Mason's Garden
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| work = House and Grounds
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref>

== Outbuildings ==
[[Image:Potomac-view-from-Gunston-Hall.jpg|thumb|300px|View of the from the outlook on the southern edge of Gunston Hall's garden, looking out towards the Potomoc]]
The outbuildings currently at Gunston Hall are reconstructed. They include a kitchen, dairy, smokehouse, and laundry. They are believed to be representative of typical support buildings for an 18th century plantation household.<ref name="GHPvisiting">
{{cite web
| url = http://look.net/gunstonhall/welcome/
| title = Visiting Gunston Hall
| accessdate = 2006-08-23
| publisher = Gunston Hall Plantation official website
}}</ref>

== Visitors' centre and museum shop ==
At the visitors' centre, tourists can view the 11-minute film "George Mason and the Bill of Rights".  Tourist can then look through the exhibit which covers Mason's political career, personal life, and 18th century plantation culture. Gunston Hall is open from 9:30 AM to 5 PM, with the exception of the holidays Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New Year's Day. Admissions prices vary based on age, from free for children in kindergarten or younger, to 8 USD for adults under the age of 60. A 45-minute tour is offered every half hour, with the last tour starting at 4:30 PM.<ref name="GHPvisiting" />

The museum shop sells souvenirs such as books, gift items, soap, food, and toys. The museum shop's stated purpose is to educate today's citizens about 18th century life in Virginia.<ref name="GHPshop" />

